rt, curious folks by subscribing here:
Instead of an ad, let me tell you about=E2=80=A6 Not Boring Capital [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/8f219cbb-0a22-49ee-939c-86ec1e71b19d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=C2=A0
Not Boring Capital invests in hard startups and tells their stories.
For the past couple of years, I=E2=80=99ve been writing about why hard star=
tups [ https://substack.com/redirect/f493bcee-adba-4911-ace3-22b305a80a7e?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are the=
 best place to invest and why I think tech companies are going to get much =
bigger [ https://substack.com/redirect/bc3e3656-6f56-40b5-86f0-53eb33a6040e=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], whil=
e investing in many of those companies at Not Boring Capital. SaaS drove th=
e past decade=E2=80=99s returns, but it will not drive the next decade=E2=
=80=99s.=C2=A0
Hard tech companies can scale without diluting early investors [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/48178f77-74a0-446c-8063-8c8ae87daa2d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to smithereens, and the =
markets they tap at scale are massive.=C2=A0I think the outcomes will be bi=
gger, and more impactful, as a result.=20
We=E2=80=99re in a great position for this shift: we write non-lead checks =
in the best hard startups we can find and provide differentiated value by e=
xplaining what they do, like we=E2=80=99ve done this year with Atomic AI [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/e336abc0-bb3e-4bdf-9a1c-43d2839e3d50?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Varda [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/02f74f73-3bdd-47ec-86af-ee63e48a53ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and Array Labs [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/47d78183-482a-4ed0-8752-33e2816ff535?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
Techno-optimism is on the rise. The future is bright. We=E2=80=99ve been co=
nsistent in our conviction throughout the bear market, and it=E2=80=99s tim=
e to accelerate.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99re an accredited investor or family office interested in lea=
rning more about investing in Not Boring Capital, let me know here and I=E2=
=80=99ll reach out:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Wednesday! What a week.=20
I don=E2=80=99t know if there=E2=80=99s a Newsletter God, but certainly if =
there is, that god was smiling on me. I wanted to write a piece on grand st=
rategy in tech, and I was gifted the perfect case study.=C2=A0
Whether you just want to sound a little more sophisticated when you explain=
 what happened at OpenAI to your family at Thanksgiving dinner or plan to b=
uild a trillion-dollar company, I=E2=80=99ve got you covered.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
OpenAI & Grand Strategy=20
There=E2=80=99s this meme that goes something like this:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CMen used to go to war, now they run tech companies.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The meme is meant to be sarcastic, to suggest that our modern pursuits are =
relatively meaningless.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s not how I read it. I think it=E2=80=99s great.=C2=A0
Count me among those who would rather our best people start companies to ac=
hieve goals no old-time general could have dreamed of than kill each other =
by the hundreds of thousands in pursuit of lesser ones.=C2=A0
Oh, you brought 600,000 young men into Russia to what? Enforce the Continen=
tal System, weaken Britain=E2=80=99s economy, expand French influence in th=
e East, and flex your military prestige? And you lost half a million of the=
m? Bravo! Quel coup de ma=C3=AEtre!=C2=A0
Do you know how many men Napoleon would have risked to control even a fract=
ion of the wonders we have at our disposal today?=C2=A0
With 770 nerds, OpenAI unlocked infinitely available intelligence. With few=
er than 10,000, SpaceX built a rocket that may one day make humans multi-pl=
anetary. With about 30,000 lines of code, Satoshi introduced a viable alter=
native to government-issued currencies.=C2=A0
The occasional board coup is a small price to pay compared to a bloody war.=
=C2=A0
In On War, 19th century military theorist Carl von Clausewitz wrote that =
=E2=80=9CWar is merely the continuation of policy by other means.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
The great strategist meant that war should always serve policy, rather than=
 the other way around. War is one way to accomplish a goal, not the goal it=
self. Means, not ends.=C2=A0
Technology, too, is just the continuation of policy by other means, but it=
=E2=80=99s a positive-sum and relatively peaceful continuation.=C2=A0
Think of it this way: at the two extremes of the climate change solution sp=
ectrum, there=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Creduce the world=E2=80=99s population to u=
nder 5 billion people=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cbuild more nuclear, solar, and =
fusion.=E2=80=9D One would lead to war, death, and misery, and the other to=
 abundance. Same ends, very different means.=C2=A0
As tech companies get much bigger [ https://substack.com/redirect/bc3e3656-=
6f56-40b5-86f0-53eb33a6040e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], as they accomplish nation-state-level goals with mor=
e limited means, their leaders need to think like the great leaders of hist=
ory, people like Augustus Caesar, Elizabeth I, and Abraham Lincoln.=C2=A0
The most ambitious tech leaders need to be grand strategists.=C2=A0
What is grand strategy?=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThe alignment of potentially unlimited aspirations with necessaril=
y limited capabilities.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s how Yale Military and Naval History Professor John L. Gaddis=
 defines it in On Grand Strategy [ https://substack.com/redirect/1f4c6338-b=
ec4-49f1-a284-630486185fc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the 2018 book he wrote to condense the lessons from h=
istory=E2=80=99s great leaders and strategists into 312 pages.=C2=A0
He adds, =E2=80=9CAlignments are necessary across time, space, and scale.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The book talks a lot about war =E2=80=94 The New York Times titled its revi=
ew, When to Wage War, and How to Win =E2=80=94 but when I read it a few wee=
ks ago while writing Tech is Going to Get Much Bigger [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/bc3e3656-6f56-40b5-86f0-53eb33a6040e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I kept thinking about how much i=
t applies to really ambitious tech companies.=20
At the end of that piece, I wrote, =E2=80=9CTake your ambition and multiply=
 it by 100. Craft a Grand Strategy. We=E2=80=99ll talk about that next time=
=2E=E2=80=9D
Then I started writing this piece, thinking about what examples I could use=
 to illustrate the themes from the book, things like=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Align aspirations and capabilities
Maintain ecological sensitivity=C2=A0
Embrace contradictions=C2=A0
Balance theory and practice
Know what it=E2=80=99s all about=C2=A0
Expect the unexpected=C2=A0
=E2=80=A6when a decade=E2=80=99s worth of examples fell into my lap over th=
e course of five days.=C2=A0
Elon Musk launched Starship, another step in his nearly 30-year pursuit of =
making humans multiplanetary.
Brian Armstrong watched the downfall of another less scrupulous competitor =
when Binance CEO CZ stepped down and pleaded guilty to money laundering cha=
rges, and Binance agreed to exit the US market.
Sam Altman and Satya Nadella emerged from an attempted OpenAI coup stronger=
 than they entered.=C2=A0
In each case, this week=E2=80=99s headlines were the result of decades of p=
atient, flexible, efforts across time, space, and scale.=C2=A0
To the grand strategist, specific companies may just be means of acquiring =
the capabilities to pursue greater aspirations. It covers time, space, and =
scale.=C2=A0
The ancient Greek poet Archilochus of Paros wrote, as Isaiah Berlin remembe=
red it, =E2=80=9CThe fox knows many things, but the hedgehog knows one big =
thing.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The grand strategist, according to Gaddis, is both fox and hedgehog: =E2=80=
=9CWe=E2=80=99d need to combine, within a single mind (our own), the hedgeh=
og=E2=80=99s sense of direction and the fox=E2=80=99s sensitivity to surrou=
ndings. While retaining the ability to function.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Grand strategists must, as Octavian and Lincoln did, =E2=80=9Cstick to thei=
r compass heading while avoiding swamps.=E2=80=9D Pursue a grand ambition r=
elentlessly, but remain flexible in your pursuit as you respond to changing=
 circumstances.=C2=A0
Each of the three examples I mentioned above deserves its own analysis. The=
 fact that there are clearly grand strategists at work in all three cases =
=E2=80=93 even if the grand strategy is only clear, even to them, with the =
benefit of hindsight =E2=80=93 shows that to build businesses that challeng=
e governments in scope and scale requires grand strategy.=C2=A0
The world=E2=80=99s largest industries are up for grabs, and new, larger on=
es are open to creation.=C2=A0
But just because they=E2=80=99re open doesn=E2=80=99t mean they=E2=80=99ll =
be easy. Cracking the really big industries is going to be a dogfight. Look=
 at crypto [ https://substack.com/redirect/2ee3ab2c-f9e8-4797-afde-a0296a8d=
a2b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. =
Or nuclear [ https://substack.com/redirect/6cfba12a-24cf-42e1-9910-23677af1=
e8c9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. =
Or AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d6415a1-7611-4210-8069-625d86ef18f6?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Or Op=
enAI.=C2=A0
The higher you climb, the stronger the opposition will be, from governments=
, incumbents, and even your own board. Their tactics will be dirty. And it =
makes sense!=C2=A0
In the context that tech is going to get much bigger as it goes after the b=
ig pools of money and power, it=E2=80=99s the rational response. Wars have =
been fought, over and over again throughout history, for much smaller prize=
s.=C2=A0
One way to approach the situation would be to complain about how unfair it =
all is. But that won=E2=80=99t work. There is no referee.=C2=A0
The other way would be to accept reality as it is and play the game on the =
field to win.=C2=A0
This is the more effective route, and the more difficult one. It requires f=
oresight and flexibility, theory and common sense, idealism and pragmatism,=
 long-term goals and short-term actions, power and vulnerability, caution a=
nd audacity.
If you take the red pill, you=E2=80=99re going to need to craft a grand str=
ategy.
There=E2=80=99s no playbook, unfortunately, just lessons from history that =
you can use as a starting point. As Gaddis writes:=C2=A0
Begin with theory and practice, both of which Clausewitz and Tolstoy respec=
t without enslaving themselves to either. It=E2=80=99s as if, in their thin=
king, abstraction and specificity reinforce each other, but never in predet=
ermined proportions. Each situation requires a balancing derived from judgm=
ent and arising from experience, skills acquired by learning from the past =
and training for the future.
Theory serves practice, which corrects theory. Be schooled in the theory an=
d flexible in its practice. =E2=80=9CAssuming stability is one of the ways =
ruins get made,=E2=80=9D Gaddis warns. =E2=80=9CResilience accommodates the=
 unexpected.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Resilience accommodates the unexpected sounds a lot like what went down at =
OpenAI over the past week.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The best way to understand the OpenAI saga is through the lens of grand str=
ategy, and the best way to understand how to apply grand strategy to tech c=
ompanies is through the lens of the OpenAI saga.=C2=A0
Sam=E2=80=99s Grand Strategy=C2=A0
Last Thursday, Sam Altman was the CEO of an AI company with a weird non-pro=
fit board. On Friday, that board fired him as CEO without warning. Today, s=
ix days later, he is back as CEO of the same AI company, with a new board a=
nd with the tech equivalent of the Mandate of Heaven.
Writing about the unpredictable chain of events that turned Octavian from 1=
8-year-old kid into Augustus Caesar, first Emperor of Rome, Gaddis says, =
=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s no way Octavian could have planned all of this. In=
stead he seized opportunities while retaining objectives. Octavian stuck to=
 his compass heading while avoiding swamps.=E2=80=9D
The same could be written of the situation at OpenAI over the past five day=
s. Altman didn=E2=80=99t plan this situation, but the outcome looks as if h=
e did.=C2=A0
For grand strategists, as Littlefinger told Varys: =E2=80=9CChaos isn=E2=80=
=99t a pit. Chaos is a ladder.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Way back in August 2008, when Altman was 24-years-old and still just the CE=
O of a YC-backed location-based social network called Loopt, Y Combinator f=
ounder Paul Graham wrote in a blog post, =E2=80=9CWhen we predict good outc=
omes for startups, the qualities that come up in the supporting arguments a=
re toughness, adaptability, determination=E2=80=A6 Sam Altman [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/ff7d10e1-7c85-4f19-9d45-93b8c570ecfc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has it. You could parachu=
te him into an island full of cannibals and come back in 5 years and he'd b=
e the king.=E2=80=9D
Eight months later, in April 2009, Graham wrote a blog post [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/e3156119-2666-4cd4-a5cd-668df966b054?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] about the five most interes=
ting founders of the last 30 years. Alongside Steve Jobs and Larry & Sergey=
, PG highlighted the then-24-year-old Altman:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9COn questions of strategy or ambition I ask =E2=80=98What would Sam=
a do?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D
That combination of strategy and ambition is essentially grand strategy. An=
d before Altman had achieved any success, Graham singled him out for posses=
sing it.=C2=A0
The way to view the past weekend isn=E2=80=99t as Altman pulling a good out=
come from a bad situation in days.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s as the result of at least 15 years of building capabilities to=
 match his aspirations, and being adaptable enough to use them when the tim=
e came.
Aligning Aspirations and Capabilities
The meta-principle from On Grand Strategy is the importance of aligning you=
r aspirations and your capabilities.=C2=A0
If there=E2=80=99s just one thing to take away, it=E2=80=99s that. So this =
is the one we=E2=80=99ll spend the most time on.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CNapoleon lost his empire by confusing aspirations with capabilitie=
s;=E2=80=9D Gaddis writes. =E2=80=9CLincoln saved his country by not doing =
so.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Time, space, and scale. Napoleon lost his empire by failing to align his ca=
pabilities with the scale of the challenge in Russia. Lincoln saved his by =
patiently waiting for the right time to issue the Emancipation Proclamation=
=2E=C2=A0
Octavian, who would become Caesar Augustus, grew his capabilities over time=
 to match his aspirations as well.=C2=A0
After the death of Julius Caesar in 44 BC, his heir Octavian waited 17 year=
s to claim the leadership of the Roman Republic that Caesar passed to him. =
In that time, he made and broke alliances, won and lost battles, built up h=
is strengths and learned to manage his weaknesses, patiently waited for his=
 enemies to eliminate themselves, and came to represent what Rome stood for=
 in the eyes of the Roman people. He built up his capabilities to match his=
 ambitions.=C2=A0
By biding his time =E2=80=93 seeing time as an ally =E2=80=93 and building =
up his capabilities to match his ambitions, he gained more power than even =
Julius Caesar had, maintaining the facade of the Roman Republic while in re=
ality leading the new Roman Empire. And he avoided his predecessor=E2=80=99=
s downfall, ruling over the Empire for the next 13 years until dying of nat=
ural causes just short of his 77th birthday.=C2=A0
How much time do men spend thinking about the Roman Empire? Maybe not enoug=
h!=C2=A0
In Choose Good Quests [ https://substack.com/redirect/ffc6d5f2-9e97-40c1-91=
ea-f9254d33e0c8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], Markie Wagner and Trae Stephens compare founders to players with=
 =E2=80=9Cspecific resources, skills, and powers.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
For a college-aged Mark Zuckerberg, building a social network for college s=
tudents was a good quest because it leveraged his specific resources, skill=
s, and powers. For Palmer Luckey, who sold Oculus to an older Zuck for $2 b=
illion, a good quest was one with higher aspirations to match his greater c=
apabilities: modernizing defense.=C2=A0
Both Zuck and Palmer are accomplishing things today that they would have fa=
iled at in their teens. If you have Level 1 capabilities, you need to level=
 up before going after Level 10 aspirations. The same was true for Octavian=
, and for Sam Altman.=C2=A0
In all of the craziness of the past week, the most striking thing to me was=
 the support Altman received: from other founders, investors, the tech comm=
unity, and most importantly, OpenAI=E2=80=99s employees.=C2=A0
When the news initially broke on Friday afternoon, given the wording in the=
 board=E2=80=99s blog post [ https://substack.com/redirect/e087461b-da9f-4b=
ee-bf4d-30c3e39a34e6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the assumption was that Altman had done something Very Bad.=
 Quickly, though, prominent founders and investors like Airbnb=E2=80=99s Br=
ian Chesky and SV Angel=E2=80=99s Ron Conway, came to his defense. Soon aft=
er, X was filled with tweets from founders who Sam had quietly gone above a=
nd beyond to help over more than a decade.=C2=A0
That shift in the narrative gave him a position of strength from which to f=
ight back, and it wouldn=E2=80=99t have been possible if he hadn=E2=80=99t =
spent the past 18 years in Silicon Valley building up his capabilities to m=
atch his aspirations.=C2=A0
When the news broke on Saturday morning that Altman and OpenAI co-founder a=
nd President Greg Brockman were already talking to investors about starting=
 something new, those rumors carried a credibility that they wouldn=E2=80=
=99t have if Altman were a fresh founder.=C2=A0
By Saturday evening, when rumors that Altman might come back as CEO started=
 swirling, it seemed almost a fait accompli. That night, Sam tweeted [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/a6c0ac8d-a32c-4b5a-8669-a7566c44a897?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=9Ci love th=
e openai team so much=E2=80=9D and the team responded with a show of force =
in the form of quote-tweet heart emojis, signifying that if Sam left, they =
would too in the most 2023 way possible.=C2=A0
Negotiations dragged on all through Sunday. It looked like Altman and Brock=
man would return and the board would resign. And then on Monday morning, we=
 woke up to a bombshell: that Twitch CEO Emmett Shear would become OpenAI C=
EO, while Sam and Greg would lead a new AI research team within Microsoft [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/a6cafbf5-df13-4115-873a-c1cb1bfd6dfa?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and bring Ope=
nAI employees with them.=C2=A0
Microsoft Satya Nadella, a grand strategist in his own right, and Sam Altma=
n were the winners, and OpenAI=E2=80=99s board were the losers.=C2=A0
But the saga didn=E2=80=99t end there. On Monday morning, at the buttcrack =
of dawn west coast time, more than 500+ of 770 OpenAI employees (over 95% o=
f employees ultimately) signed a letter threatening to quit and join Sam an=
d Greg at the new Microsoft AI thing unless all current board members resig=
n and a new board reinstates Sam and Greg.=C2=A0
Over the past couple of days, it became clear that the board=E2=80=99s reas=
ons for firing Sam were shaky at best, and that whatever the facts, Altman =
had the support of the people.=C2=A0
As of this morning, Sam is back in as CEO, with a new board.
Altman played the situation perfectly. He drew on a career=E2=80=99s worth =
of built-up capabilities and relationships, and maintained flexibility on t=
he specifics in pursuit of the long-term goal by showing a willingness to w=
ork towards AGI at a new startup, within Microsoft, or at OpenAI.=C2=A0
It was downright Octavian.=C2=A0
When Octavian reached the height of his power after the downfall of his riv=
al Antony, writes Gaddis:=C2=A0
He secured authority by appearing to renounce it, most dramatically on the =
first day of 27 when he unexpectedly gave up all his responsibilities. The =
surprised senate had no choice but to forbid this and to award Octavian the=
 title of princeps (=E2=80=9Cfirst citizen=E2=80=9D) =E2=80=93 as well as a=
 new name: Augustus.
The board, meanwhile, failed miserably in its coup by ignoring the lessons =
of grand strategy.=C2=A0
As Gaddis warns, =E2=80=9CThe principle, for both Augustine and Machiavelli=
, reflects common sense: if you have to use force, don=E2=80=99t destroy wh=
at you=E2=80=99re trying to preserve.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
They almost destroyed the company, and ended up destroying their oversight =
over it.=C2=A0
Why?=C2=A0
Their capabilities didn=E2=80=99t match their aspirations.=C2=A0
In fact, they seemed to have wildly misjudged their capabilities, believing=
 that the company=E2=80=99s wonky governance structure gave them the leeway=
 to do as they wished, but not realizing that real power doesn=E2=80=99t co=
me from pieces of paper, but from the will of the people.=C2=A0
They didn=E2=80=99t realize that OpenAI is nothing without its people.=C2=
=A0
And they didn=E2=80=99t maintain ecological sensitivity. They didn=E2=80=99=
t understand the tech community well enough to understand that most people =
would support Altman, didn=E2=80=99t understand the investors well enough t=
o know how much pressure they would apply, and didn=E2=80=99t know the comp=
any well enough to realize that its people would walk. They didn=E2=80=99t =
pick up on the subtle vibe shift from safetyism to acceleration, and failed=
 to anticipate how little support they would receive.=C2=A0
They came at the king, and missed, and made him the Emperor.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Becoming a Grand Strategist
Here=E2=80=99s the thing: as crazy as this past week was, things are going =
to keep getting crazier.=C2=A0
I keep banging this drum, but I can=E2=80=99t bang it loudly enough: things=
 will keep getting crazier.
The things that tech companies build in the coming years will blow even my =
optimistic mind and give them power on a scale no company has had. They=E2=
=80=99ll rival nation-states. They already rival nation-states =E2=80=93 Ap=
ple=E2=80=99s $383 billion in 2023 revenue would rank it 41st in the world =
in national GDP, sandwiched between Hong Kong and South Africa, and while r=
evenue and GDP aren=E2=80=99t perfect comps, those are serious numbers =E2=
=80=93 but they=E2=80=99ll rival more powerful ones.=C2=A0
Battles like one we all just witnessed at OpenAI, like the decades-long att=
ack on nuclear, like the government=E2=80=99s anti-crypto Operation Chokepo=
int 2.0, will become more common, not less.=C2=A0
And that=E2=80=99s fair. The stakes are that high.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99re reading this and you have ambitions to make the world a d=
ifferent place [ https://substack.com/redirect/59ebe63a-0864-4a68-8748-e7c2=
152fa6c1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ], know that coming in, but don=E2=80=99t let it deter you. Know that it=
=E2=80=99s what you=E2=80=99re up against, and start crafting your own gran=
d strategy.=C2=A0
Acquire capabilities to match your ambitions. Maintain ecological sensitivi=
ty. Build alliances. Embrace chaos. Know theory while accepting that it won=
=E2=80=99t survive contact with practice. Remain flexible in tactics and st=
eadfast in ambition.=C2=A0
Certainly, read On Grand Strategy [ https://substack.com/redirect/1f4c6338-=
bec4-49f1-a284-630486185fc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I captured a fraction of the lessons from the book. =
Live in the stories that Gaddis tells, put yourself in the shoes of history=
=E2=80=99s greats.=C2=A0
Coming up on the holiday season, when we all get a little time to relax and=
 reflect, think about the final theme from the book: Know What It=E2=80=99s=
 All About.
What are you working towards, and why?=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s never been a better time for a small group of passionate pe=
ople to change the course of history, for the better, bloodlessly. Go craft=
 your grand strategy and get to work.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/60262ef9-f437-4f3c-bad7-a87b3=
437fba5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. Have a Happy Thanksgiving, and we=E2=80=99ll =
be back in your inbox with the Weekly Dose on Friday!
Thanks for reading,
Packy

